<p>
	People said I'd have a hard time finding anything but meat on the menus in Buenos Aires. So I crammed a bunch of dried fruit and energy bars in my carry-on bag, convinced that my vegetarian food preferences would disadvantage me at every 
	<em>
		porte&ntilde;o
	</em>
	restaurant. 
</p>
<p>
	I shouldn't have been so anxious. Unlike New Orleans, or what I experienced of Spain, Buenos Aires offered plenty of food which didn't use dead animal bits as ingredients. I abandoned my energy bars the very first day. 
</p>
<p>
	True, there's a lot of beef on a typical Argentine menu. The beef eaters in my tour group reported that the meat was very different from that in the U.S.&ndash; more tender, not aged, cooked more fully, offered in cuts they hadn't seen before. So I guess Argentine beef is a real treat if meat is to your liking. A couple of times, though, the meat eaters encountered cuisine items which seemed too carnivorous even for them. The guidebooks warn us gringos from sampling the full gamut of 
	<em>
		parilla
	</em>
	offerings. 
</p>
