<p>
	One of the best surprises Buenos Aires gave me was how excellent even the most humble restaurant was. There seem to be a million fluorescent-lit, nondescript, look-alike chain pizza restaurants, the kind I don't patronize much at home. And yet each of these I went to in Buenos Aires had an extensive menu, courtly wait staff, and often a full bar. The menus always included 
	<em>
		pasta casera</em>, fresh pasta, in a variety of interesting sauces, many of them meatless. Salads? I rarely order these at home, because they're usually tasteless, overchilled iceberg lettuce topped with carrot slivers. But in Buenos Aires salads are meal-sized combinations of excellent leaf lettuce and countless other ingredients; not a wisp of iceberg in sight. 
</p>
