	</p>
</div>
<p>
	I often found the restaurant portion sizes too big, even though my appetite is rather large. Fortunately, Argentina has contributed <em>empanadas</em> to world snacking culture. These modestly sized pastries are sold at (to me) absurdly low prices, and just one or two usually filled me up. Of course, they most often come filled with meat, but in most places there are also imaginative vegetarian fillings, such as spinach and kale. 
</p>
<p>
	Another food to try was ice cream. Since working in an ice cream factory a while ago I've pretty much lost my interest in the stuff, but I'd heard Buenos Aires ice cream praised so much I decided to order a small cup. I was pleased to see many flavors completely unfamiliar to me: not only were the names in Spanish, but the ingredients were tropical fruits we don't often see in the States. I pondered a while, and finally chose 
	<em>
		marr&oacute;n glac&eacute;</em>, because one of my favorite 
	<em>
		Guardia Vieja
	</em>
	tango recordings is of a song called that. 
</p>
