</div>
<p>
	If I have any complaint about Buenos Aires restaurant menus, it's about the lack of spice in the food. Not only are hot peppers missing, but even black pepper, and strangely for a place with so much Italian heritage, pronounced garlic flavor. I was reminded of how food can taste in the American Midwest, where people seem to have the same dislike of pepper and spice. Finally, at one restaurant, my eggplant appetizer tasted unabashedly of garlic, and the table even had black pepper freely available from a grinder. 
</p>
