<p>
Remarkably, despite my <a href="http://www.twobanjos.com/read/buenosaires/2006/me-talk-bueno-one-day.php">poor command of Spanish</a>, I experienced only one episode of getting meat in my restaurant meal.  This mishap was entirely my fault: I saw <em>tortilla espa&ntilde;ola</em> on the menu, and thought I was ordering the egg-and-potatoes tapas bar staple I'd enjoyed in Spain.  I was so confident in my choice that I didn't ask the waiter if the dish had meat in it.  The waiter grumbled a bit when I objected to the sausage omelette he served me ("<em>No es carne; es chorizo</em>") but he was gracious about bringing me a <em>tortilla con papa</em>, which was more like what I had envisioned.  Another vegetarian in our group had an unhappy experience with the <em>caprese</em> filling of her empanada.  Unlike the mozzarella, tomato, and basil combination called <em>caprese</em> in the States, this mixture included big chunks of ham.  Moral of these stories:  always ask your server whether a menu item has meat, fish, pork, or chicken in it.
</p>




<h2 class="tips">
	Tips 
</h2>
<ul>
	<li>
	On many of these pizza restaurant menus there is a section marked <em>men&uacute; light</em>.  Though these are supposed to be options for dieters, the items there are nothing like the grim cottage-cheese-and-beef-patty platters on offer in the States.  Instead, there are often several interesting vegetarian choices, such as soy croquettes or squash-filled raviolis 
	</li>
	<li>There are quite a few reputable all- or mostly vegetarian restaurants in Buenos Aires.  Astoundingly, I visited none of them, but they're on my list for next time
	</li>
	<li>Nobody's confirmed this for me, but I suspect that the phrase <em>sin carne</em> doesn't exactly translate to the English phrase <em>without meat</em>, i.e., without dead animal bits.  My encounter with the server who didn't consider chorizo <em>carne</em> strengthens my hypothesis:  I don't think he was dismissing my concern about eating <em>carne</em>, but helpfully pointing out that <em>carne</em>, whatever that means in Argentina, was absent from my sausage omelette.  I'm inclined to think <em>carne</em> means beef, or steak</li>
</ul>
